## Testing Strategy

### Unit Tests

- `detectFramework()` with mock directories containing various config files
- `detectPackageManager()` with each lockfile type present
- `generateDockerfile()` for each framework/mode combination (already implemented -- verify tests exist)
- `BuildQueue` cancel-and-replace behavior (already implemented -- verify tests exist)
- `saveCache()` / `restoreCache()` with mocked S3 client
- Build log secret scrubbing (patterns: API keys, tokens, passwords, connection strings)

### Integration Tests

- Framework detection on real Next.js project directories
- Docker `buildImage()` with a minimal Dockerfile (requires Docker daemon)
- Docker `runContainer()` / `stopContainer()` lifecycle (requires Docker daemon)
- `DockerProvider` full create/update/delete cycle (requires Docker daemon)
- `BuildRunner.run()` end-to-end with a test repository (requires Docker + S3)

### Manual Verification

- Clone a Next.js server-mode repo, detect framework, generate Dockerfile, build image
- Clone a Next.js static-export repo, verify static mode detection
- Clone a repo with custom Dockerfile, verify it uses the user Dockerfile
- Verify build logs appear in S3 after build completion
- Trigger two builds for the same project, verify cancel-and-replace in queue

